11/ Unpacking:

A push to activate something that doesn’t have clear, overwhelming consensus through a node that is not #Bitcoin Core through means that are controversial (ST) in a short time frame blew people up.

But, again some misunderstandings…

11/…in a Speedy Trial style of activation, like with Taproot.

People likely got nervous because 1) the ST would start in a short time after that post 2) it would be in a node client other than #Bitcoin Core 3) some thought Rubin would do a UASF 4) others thought he should…

10/ The heated discussion picked up pace after BIP 119 author @JeremyRubin wrote a blog post saying:

“Within a week from [Apr. 17], you will find software builds for a CTV #Bitcoin Client.”

The client would enable miners to signal whether they intended to enforce CTV rules…

9/ So if CTV is simple, why all the controversy and heated discussions?

There are likely two aspects: myths (debunked above) and activation specifics into #Bitcoin (explained below).

7/ But won’t governments have new tools available to create #Bitcoin whitelists with CTV?

No, CTV does not change the dynamic that only you can place that restriction.

But didn’t @aantonop say that?

No, he was talking that recursive covenants might - which CTV does not enable.

6/ Who would be able to place restrictions on your #bitcoin? 

You. 

This is true for any Bitcoin transaction: the receiver is the one to set restrictions - not the sender.

Only you can place spending restrictions on your BTC, and the same would be true in a world with CTV.

5/ CTV would give you more control, beyond the unlocking.

You would be able to define “where” some of your #bitcoin can be spent and “how much” of it.

This could e.g. help you mitigate against theft with a vault - preventing an attacker from sweeping all your funds.

But…

Good morning #Bitcoin￼ 

Metrics are looking good⚡️

4/ Aren’t restrictions on #bitcoin spending opposed to sovereignty?

As said above, today you can already place restrictions on BTC spending.

E.g. you can define “when” it can be spent or require more than one private key.

But you can’t control what happens after unlocking…

3/ What could CTV bring to #Bitcoin ?

CTV could enable some use cases, including: vaults, congestion control, payment pools and improvements to Lightning.

They mostly focus on enhancing security for those using it and scalability for the network.

2/ What is BIP 119?

It’s a soft fork proposal from 2019/2020 to add a new opcode to #Bitcoin - OP_CTV.

CTV would enable users to restrict where they can spend some of their own BTC (beyond ensuring the correct private key is used and timing rules are respected).

Aka covenant.

1/ Myths about #Bitcoin CTV (BIP 119) have in part fueled the recent heated discussions.

Here’s an explainer of what CTV can and cannot do, as well as a deeper dive into the controversies.
